<tt>Fri Aug 15  6:33:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Oh, I know there were some wheelers and dealers on both sides of this.  Grunts who traded for things they wanted in the bush and guys in the rear areas who wanted the souvenirs to sell or ship home.  Neither had uses for what they had and both had a desire to acquire.  I would say that is Capitalism at it's best!<br>
I didn't open this thread for me.  I wanted some discussion started for guys who have had their experience discounted.  Either by themselves or someone else.<br>
It was an issue for me.  I have processed this and I now understand that all the things done in country in a support role was valuable.  I am grateful for the responses posted here for me.  And the stories provided.<br>
Yes, I too have stories about stuff found in the field and brought back to base.  It is fun to play.  We even had a guy who had several folks in town making belt buckles with the red star in them.  Made a ton of money.<br>
I would like to see everyone in D.C. on Veteran's Day. November 11th.  This will be a celebration of survival and recognition of those who gave their all.   
